      <a className="btn" href="mailto:james@aescia.com?subject=Aescia%20trial%20discussion%20(from%20MEDTEQ%2B)&body=Hi%20James%2C%0A%0AI%20scanned%20your%20card%20at%20MEDTEQ%2B.%20We%E2%80%99d%20like%20to%20explore%20a%20trial.%0A%0AOrg%3A%0ARole%3A%0ACohort%20of%20interest%3A%20(e.g.%20CTS%2C%20HF%2C%20COPD%2C%20peds)%0ABest%20contact%3A%0A%0AThanks%2C">Email directly</a>
    </div>

    <p className="mini" style={{ marginTop: ".8rem" }}>
      Short on time? The fastest path is: <strong>pick a cohort</strong> → <strong>define escalation</strong> → <strong>run a 8–12 week pilot</strong> with workflow + outcomes metrics.
    </p>
  </div>

  <div className="grid">
    <div className="panel">
      <h3>What Aescia actually does</h3>
      <ul className="bullets">
        <li><strong>Captures patient-reported outcomes</strong> after discharge using structured prompts (not “random chat”).</li>
        <li><strong>Flags concerning trajectories</strong> so clinicians see who needs attention first.</li>
        <li><strong>Supports consistent escalation pathways</strong> (site-specific rules, transparent logic).</li>
        <li><strong>Creates an auditable trail</strong> of follow-up attempts, responses, and escalation events.</li>
      </ul>

      <div className="hr" />

      <h3>Why teams care</h3>
      <ul className="bullets">
        <li>Earlier detection of deterioration → fewer avoidable representations and complications.</li>
        <li>More consistent follow-up → less “who called whom, when?” chaos.</li>
        <li>Clear evaluation metrics → easier to justify scale-up and funding.</li>
      </ul>
    </div>

    <div className="panel">
      <h3>Where we are today</h3>
      <ul className="bullets">
        <li><strong>Actively progressing a first trial</strong> (cardiothoracic surgery pathway) with a focus on real-world feasibility + outcomes.</li>
        <li><strong>Built to be clinician-in-the-loop</strong>, with conservative safety and escalation design.</li>
        <li><strong>Designed for governance</strong>: traceability, pathway versioning, and evaluation readiness.</li>
      </ul>

      <Callout type="info">
        We’re looking for trial partners who want to improve discharge safety without adding an unsustainable workload.
      </Callout>

      <h3>Ideal pilot partner profile</h3>
      <ul className="bullets">
        <li>Has a high-impact cohort (e.g., major surgery, heart failure, complex respiratory, pediatrics).</li>
        <li>Has an existing escalation owner (nurse navigator, CNC, NP, registrar team, virtual ward).</li>
        <li>Wants measurable results (readmissions, length of stay, ED re-presentations, workload).</li>
      </ul>
    </div>
  </div>

  <div className="hr" />

  <div className="panel">
    <h3>What a trial could look like (simple + credible)</h3>
    <ul className="bullets">
      <li><strong>Duration:</strong> 8–12 weeks</li>
      <li><strong>Cohort:</strong> 100–300 discharges (or smaller to start if governance is heavy)</li>
      <li><strong>Workflow metrics:</strong> response rate, time-to-escalation, clinician time per escalated patient</li>
      <li><strong>Outcome metrics:</strong> ED re-presentations, readmissions, complications caught earlier, patient experience</li>
      <li><strong>Operational metrics:</strong> bed-day impact (where measurable), discharge confidence, escalations resolved remotely</li>
    </ul>
  </div>

  <div className="faq">
    <details>
      <summary>Is this “AI making clinical decisions”?</summary>
      <div style={{ marginTop: ".6rem" }}>
        No. The core product is structured follow-up + escalation workflow. Where AI can help is summarisation,
        signal extraction, and helping clinicians triage attention — but escalation remains clinician-controlled.
      </div>
    </details>

    <details>
      <summary>How hard is implementation?</summary>
      <div style={{ marginTop: ".6rem" }}>
        The design goal is minimal friction. A pilot can run without deep integration at first.
        If it works, integration becomes worth doing (and easier to justify internally).
      </div>
    </details>

    <details>
      <summary>What do you need from a hospital to start?</summary>
      <div style={{ marginTop: ".6rem" }}>
        A cohort owner, an escalation pathway, a small working group (clinical + ops + governance),
        and agreement on what “success” looks like. We’ll do the heavy lifting on setup and evaluation design.
      </div>
    </details>
  </div>

